The M&M Proposition II is an assumption wherein the cost of equity of the company increases along with the amount of debt. 

In order to solve for the formula for the cost of equity, we must first remember this:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{Return on equity}&=\dfrac{\text{Net income}}{\text{Equity}}
\end{aligned}$$

From this, we can then substitute the formula for the net income into the formula for the return on equity in Step 2:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{R}_E&=\dfrac{(\text{EBIT}-\text{R}_D \times\text{D})\times(1-\text{T}_C)}{\text{E}}
\end{aligned}$$

From the M&M Proposition II without taxes, we can then rewrite the formula as:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{R}_E&=[\text{EBIT}(1-\text{T}_C)/\text{E}]-[\text{R}_D(\text{D}/\text{E})(1-\text{T}_C)]
\end{aligned}$$

We can then represent the first part of the equation in a different manner which will make the formula become:

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{R}_E&=\text{R}_U\text{V}_U/\text{E}-[\text{R}_D(\text{D}/\text{E})(1-\text{T}_C)]
\end{aligned}$$

Where, 

$$\begin{aligned}
\text{R}_U&=\text{Cost of unlevered equity}\\
\text{V}_U&=\text{Value of unlevered equity}
\end{aligned}$$
